E-mail is not a good fit for -professional- correspondence.

E-mail senders are not authenticated by default, which invites impersonation / scams / phishing.
E-mail user agents load external entities by default, which is a security risk and infringes on privacy.
E-mails are not confidential by default, no end-to-end encryption.
E-mails do not support threading, but real life discussions aren't linear.
E-mails disclose recipients and cc:s by default, which is noisy + privacy problem.
E-mails are 'reply all':ed to, which is a privacy problem and noisy.
E-mails end up in junk boxes.
E-mails drown in spam.
E-mails are filtered out by robots / rules, even if they are legit.
E-mail addresses can't be rotated, once disclosed they are forever in the hands of scammers and spammers.

People loses their minds when emails are involved. They click on links, reply to old threads, send sensitive files to the wrong recipients.

There are ways to mitigate some of these problems, but they are not used on a large scale.

When it's easy for users to make mistakes, they are not at fault — the system is.








